To add udmabuf (u-dma-buf) to a PetaLinux project, you must integrate the kernel module source code and configure the device tree to define the DMA buffer properties. 

1. Integrate the Kernel Module First, clone the official repository and create a PetaLinux module template. Replace the placeholder files with the source code from the repository. 

# Clone the udmabuf repository
git clone https://github.com/ikwzm/udmabuf

# Create and enable the module in PetaLinux
petalinux-create -t modules --name u-dma-buf --enable

# Copy the source code into the PetaLinux recipe directory
cp udmabuf/u-dma-buf.c project-spec/meta-user/recipes-modules/u-dma-buf/files/
cp udmabuf/u-dma-buf-ioctl.h project-spec/meta-user/recipes-modules/u-dma-buf/files/

2. Configure the Device Tree Edit the user-specific device tree file located at project-spec/meta-user/recipes-bsp/device-tree/files/system-user.dtsi to define the buffer size, name, and synchronization mode. The compatible string must be ikwzm,u-dma-buf. 

/include/ "system-conf.dtsi"

/ {
    udmabuf@0x00 {
        compatible = "ikwzm,u-dma-buf";
        device-name = "udmabuf0";
        minor-number = <0>;
        size = <0x4000000>; // 64 MB
        sync-mode = <1>;
        sync-always;
    };
};

3. Build and Deploy Rebuild the PetaLinux project to include the module. You can either build the entire system or just the module and root filesystem. 

petalinux-build

Upon booting the target, the module will instantiate the device node (e.g., /dev/udmabuf0), allowing user-space applications to map the DMA buffer via mmap. 
